Part I - Ford GoBike Data Exploration¶

by Tayo Olowu¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area within the month of February, 2019 (source).

The idea behind bike sharing is to enjoy the joys of riding a bike around a city without needing to own one. The bikes are of high quality, too. Bike-sharing is essentialy a bicycle rental program. It's like renting a car, but the object being rented is a bicycle. For this particular dataset, the rental program (called Bay Wheels initially, later renamed to Ford GoBike) offers bike rentals 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, all-year round. Thus, we should expect to see at least one night-time rental in our dataset.

For our purposes, we'll refer to all trip-takers (people who rented the bikes and took the trips) as 'users'. Rentals will also be referred to as 'trips'. We obviously don't have enough information to know the 'true' duration of each journey. In this dataset, a 'trip' simply means the time the rental started and the time it officially ended. It also includes information about the rental stations.

The Dataset's variables¶

  • bike_id - an integer identifying the bike that was rented.
  • member_birth_year - the year in which the user was born.
  • member_gender - the user's gender.
  • user_type - what rental plan did the particular user follow? Two unique values here - Customer and Subscriber. Customers rent the bikes for a day or less, while Subscribers are subscribed to longer-term rental plans like a month or up to a year.
  • bike_share_for_all_trip - this is a rental plan which is more affordable than the single-trip or single-day rental, though not as cheap as the full membership.
  • start_time - what time did the trip start?
  • end_time - what time did the trip end?
  • duration_sec - useful summary information telling us how long the trip lasted.
  • start_station_id, start_station_name - information identifying the station where the bike was rented from.
  • start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude - information identifying the geographic location of the start station.
  • end_station_id, end_station_name - information identifying the station where the bike was dropped at (thus ending the trip).
  • end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude - information identifying the geographic location of the end station.

From the above statistics, we can see a problem with the member_birth_years column - one user was born in 1878 apparently. We can also see a problem with the trip duration (seconds). The maximum is about 85,444 seconds which is about 23 hours long. It's unlikely that any person rode a bicycle straight for 23 hours (even if it's an automatic bicycle), so that value suggests a slight flaw in how we interpret the trip duration data.

Once again, the trip duration only represents the time between when the rental was started, and when it was ended. It's entirely possible that a user started their rental, went and stayed home for 24 hours then ended their rental the next day! Still, let's have faith that most of the trips were fairly 'normal'. Let's explore the data some more.

Cleanliness Issues¶

Upon cursory exploration of the data we've noticed the following issues...

Quality Issues¶

  • start_time and end_time values are too precise.
  • start_time and end_time columns contain strings instead of dtime objects.
  • The duration_sec column is presented in seconds instead of the more appropriate unit of minutes (considering the minimum and maximum values in that column).
  • There are rows whose trip duration is unreasonably long.
  • The member_birth_year values are stored as floats instead of ints.
  • The member_birth_year column contains unusual values such as 1878.
  • start_station_id and end_station_id are stored as floats rather than ints.
  • The bike_share_for_all_trip column is better off stored as booleans rather than strings.
  • For some columns, there are missing values or NaN values in the table.

Tidiness Issues¶

  • The table contains two observational units: user information (user_type, birth year, etc. and bike id), and station information (name, location for both stop and start).

So, we'll quickly clean those issues before we move on. For the sake of convenience and conciseness, we won't clean all of these quality issues. We'll only clean enough to facilitate our data exploration. We also won't clean the tidiness issue - all the exploration will be done with a single dataframe.

Quick Cleanup¶

# defining a function to facilitate cleaning
# it collects the indexes that satisfy a condition
def collect_indices(df,column,cond):
    # cond is a function which applies a conditional test to the item.
    inds = []
    pairs = tuple(zip(df.index, df[column]))
    for pair in pairs:
        ind = pair[0]
        item = pair[1]
        if cond(item):
            inds.append(item)
    return inds
In [9]:
# defining a function to facilitate testing
def column_passed(df, column, fail_cond):
    # fail cond is a function which tests for failure.
    passed = True
    pairs = tuple(zip(df.index, df[column]))
    for pair in pairs:
        ind, item = pair[0], pair[1]
        if fail_cond(item):
            print(f'TEST FAILED, {item} FOUND AT INDEX {ind}.')
            passed = False
            break
    return passed

Issue #3: The duration_sec column is presented in seconds rather than minutes¶

We won't modify the duration_sec column. Instead, we'll create a new column called 'duration_min'. Each minute will be rounded up or down, resulting in a slight loss in accuracy but we'll still have the duration_sec column to rely on if we care about that much accuracy.

In [14]:
# this function rounds a number up or down based on simple rules
def abs_round(x):
    x = abs(x)
    diff = x-int(x) # 0<= diff < 1
    if diff>=0.5:
        return int(x)+1
    elif diff<0.5:
        return int(x)
In [15]:
# apply the map, create the new column
dur_min = tuple(map(lambda sec:abs_round(sec/60), df_ford.duration_sec))
df_ford['duration_min'] = dur_min

Although we said the unreasonably long trip durations were a cleanliness issue, we won't drop them. The rows in question could contain useful information apart from trip duration. Instead, during our visualisation phase we'll make sure to sample the dataframe for rows with 'reasonable' trip durations, or at least change the scaling of our plots.

To facilitate the cleaning (and visualisation) process, we'll define a new column indicating the ages of each user. We'll find the most recent date from the dataset and subtract the member_birth_year from that most recent date.

Since we've dropped those rows, we've almost guaranteed that all trips present in the dataset started and ended on the same weekday.

To be sure that this is really the case, we have to recall that the longest trip duration is about 23 hours rather than days. If that were not the case, it's possible (though unlikely) that a trip started on Monday then ended the next week's Monday. But because no trip is longer than a day, we can rule those cases out and conclude that all trips in this dataset started and ended on the same weekday. Thus, we can drop the end_day column and rename the start_day column to 'weekday'.

In [33]:

df_ford.rename(columns={'start_day':'weekday'}, inplace=True)

Now we can move on to exploring the dataset.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

At this stage, we have 174592 rows in the dataset. Each row describes a single trip taken by a user. There are also 13 columns in the dataset, some of which were crafted manually from the original existing data. Each column describes an attribute of the trip in question. The columns include information about when and where the trip began, when and where it stopped, how long it lasted, as well as some information about the users who took the trips.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The trip duration will be our main point of focus here. How does the duration of each trip relate to the other relevant features? Does subscription type correlate with trip duration? What about the start and end station? What about the day of the week or the time of the day? How about the user's gender? Also, what could be responsible for the unusually long trip durations?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe the time of the day, and the day of the week will have the strongest relationship with respect to trip duration. The age of the user will probably corellate inversely with trip duration - naively we'd expect that the older the user, the shorter the trip duration. There may be a weak correlation with respect to gender, but there could also be none.

The rentals cost money, and the pricing rates depend on the user's rental plan. Are they subscribers who pay monthly or annual fees, or are they regular customers paying for one-time trips which last a day or less? Are they enrolled in the Bike-Share-for-All option? It's tempting to suggest that the Subscriber status is cheaper than the Customer status, but I don't expect it to be that simple. After all, if a user truly wants to use the service once and only once, there's no point paying the extra money for the monthly plan. Still, we'll see what the trends are.

The journey path i.e. start_station-to-end_station pair probably also influences trip duration somehow, but the logistics of displaying that data means we won't consider that here.

Univariate Exploration¶

Let's define useful functions and objects.¶

In [43]:
# function for quick histograms
def sketch_hist(column,stepsize,custom_x=False,color='orange'):
    if custom_x:
        # expects column to be a numpy array
        x = column
        lowest = np.min(column) # or amin
        largest = np.max(column)
    elif not custom_x:
        x = df_ford[column]
        lowest = df_ford[column].min()
        largest = df_ford[column].max()
    bins = np.arange(lowest,largest+stepsize,stepsize)
    plt.hist(x=x, bins=bins, color=color)
In [44]:
# for plotting the labels.
def put_labels(title, x_label, y_label):
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)

# for conveniently placing custom tick labels
def place_ticks(least, most, step, offset=0, tick_labels=[], axis='x'):
    tick_placement = np.arange(least+offset,
                      most+step+offset,
                      step)
    tick_labels = np.array([i for i in range(least, most+step, step)]) # modfified this
    if axis=='x':
        plt.xticks(tick_placement, tick_labels)
    elif axis=='y':
        plt.yticks(tick_placement, tick_labels)

How do we explain the long tail of the plot? Either there exist superhumans capable of riding a bicycle for nearly a day, or it reflects a problem with how the service was used, or how the data was recorded. We can't discard those observations since they contain other useful information (such as user type, member gender, etc). In any case, the visuals show that most of the trip durations are around 11 minutes long.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

There were a few unusually large trip durations. Some lasted for nearly 24 hours. Unless some of the users had superhuman levels of endurance, these are likely mistakes from the data recording process.

Both the start hour and weekday followed bimodal distributions. Early Morning and Late Afternoon boasted the highest number of trips, and Tuesday and Thursday boasted the highest number of trips compared to the other start times and days respectively.

The gender distribution was not what I naively expected. it mostly skewed male. I can't think of any factors that could've caused this (not any factors present in the data) so I won't explore that too much.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I decided to create categorical (but ordinal) bins from the age and start time data. The only reason is that it felt natural, and made for impler visualisations. Although the data had trips with unusually long durations, I did not remove them because I felt they contained useful information not related to trip durationand that it was a point worth exploring. I instead changed the x-scaling of the histogram and made it logarithmic.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Now that we've gotten a broad overview of our variables, we'll examine the following relationships:

  • subscription type and trip duration (relative)
  • bike_shared and user_type (the counts are the z-axis)
  • time started and time ended (categorical vs categorical)
  • start hour and weekday. Compare weekdays versus weekends. Is it still bimodal?
  • gender and station location (categorical vs categorical - gender is independent)
  • gender and time started (categorical vs categorical-ordinal. Gender is independent)
  • station location and time started (categorical-nominal vs categorical-ordinal. Station loc is independent)

But first let's get a broad overview of the relationships using a facet grid.

To make our bivariate explorations far more convenient, we'll define two useful functions. The first retrieves categorical-categorical distributions, the second describes the distribution in words.

In [78]:
# get the proportional distribution of dependent categorical variable, for a specific independent categorical var
# intended for categorical-categorical exploration.

def get_categorical_props(indep, specific_indep, dep, data=df_ford): # get proportions
    # filters the data frame. Not the most elegant, but it's all i can do for now
    df = data[data[indep]==specific_indep]
    df_indep_counts = df[dep].value_counts(ascending=True)
    n_users = sum(df_indep_counts.values)
    
    prop_dict = dict(zip(df_indep_counts.index, df_indep_counts.values))
    # convert to proportions
    for dependent_type in df_indep_counts.index:
        prop_dict[dependent_type] = int(10000*prop_dict[dependent_type]/n_users)/100
    return prop_dict
In [79]:
# sometimes we need numbers
def props_in_words(indep, dep, data=df_ford, lb='-'):
    # lb means line break
    indep_values = data[indep].unique()
    for indep_value in indep_values:
        cat_props = get_categorical_props(indep, indep_value, dep, data)
        for dep_value, percent in cat_props.items():
            print(f'{percent} percent of {indep_value} match {dep_value}')
        print(50*lb)

Bivariate Plot 3: Start hour¶

3A: Start hour and End hour¶

In the Univariate Exploration part we saw that the start and end hours had a bimodal distribution with respect to the counts. In other words, there were two times of the day for which many (though not necessarily most) of the trips either started or ended. The trip-taking rate was steady then suddenly spiked and dropped around 7 to 8 AM, and 4 to 5 PM. One possible explanation is that for 7-8 AM, most of the users wanted to get to work. For 4-5 PM, most of the users wanted to leave work for somewhere else. Considering that many users were around working age (25 to 45 years old), it's a feasible explanation though further data would be needed.

However, if we plot both the start and end hours side-by-side, we notice that their shapes are roughly similar, with small differences in height. Why is this?

In [98]:
# start and end time together
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
put_labels('NUMBER OF TRIPS STARTED/ENDED AT GIVEN HOUR',
           'hour of day', 'number of trips')
place_ticks(least=0, most=24, step=1, offset=0.45)

# we need more control so we can't use sketch_hist
bins = np.arange(0, 24+1, 1)
plt.hist(x=get_hours('start_time'), bins=bins, label='started', width=0.45, color='black') ;
plt.hist(x=get_hours('end_time'), bins=bins+0.45, label='ended', width=0.45, color='red') ;
plt.legend() ;

One possible explanation¶

The reason for the similarity in shape is that most of the trip durations were fairly short.

It may seem obvious that the start and end hour plots should have the same shape, but that's not necessarily guaranteed. We can imagine a different Bike-sharing program with poor logistics which only has one (or sufficiently few) end stations, and all those end stations open and close during a very small window of the day.

All else being equal (e.g start stations being available, people starting trips at the same time), the poor logistics of the end stations would force all trips to end within the same narrow window of time on any given day. In that case, the modality of the end hours would look unimodal because no matter when the users started, they could only end their trips around a specific time of day.

However, this Bike-sharing program doesn't seem to be like that. Most users could end their trips shortly after they started, and considering the broad geographical distribution of the Bike-sharing program this could indicate good logistics. But what could explain the differences in height?

Explaining the differences in height¶

Let's make a few assumptions. First, we assume that a vast majority of the users ended their trip at most one hour after they started. This is justified from the average trip duration. What this means for the visualisation is that the height of the ending bars is due to...

  • Users who started in the previous hour (e.g started by 10:00 AM and ended by 11:00 AM, or started by 10:50 AM and ended by 11:10 AM)
  • Users who started in the same hour (e.g. started by 10:30 AM and ended by 10:40 AM)

For a given hour, there are two possible cases, keeping in mind that the average trip duration is fairly short (about 11 minutes). Let's say it's an hour at best.

  • The start bar is taller than the end bar. There are two feasible explanations for this.

    • The first explanation for this is that a number of the users started late within the current hour and (after a short trip) ended early within the next hour. For example, 10:54 AM to 11:04 AM is just a ten-minute trip but it crosses an hour boundary.
    • The second is that a number of the users started early within the current hour (e.g. 10:00 AM) and after a long trip duration (say, 50 minutes) they ended within the next hour (e.g. 10:10 AM to 11:00 AM).

  • The start bar is shorter than the end bar.

    • Considering the above case, the greater height of the end bar comes from people who started in the previous hour, as well as some people who started within the same hour.

If the above explanations are correct, the key insight is as follows - The similarity of the distributions reinforces the fact that most of the trip durations were fairly short, and could be ended conveniently.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

What stood out to me is the fact that the start hours and end hour counts have roughly the same shape, and even peak and taper at the same hours. We saw one explanation for this - that it reinforces the fact that most of the trip durations were fairly short, and suggests that this specific Bike-share programme had good logistics.

There were also other interesting points to note.

  • The longest trip durations were due to younger users
  • Users of unspecified gender had the longest average trip durations, if we group by gender.

  • We noticed that the counts for start hour was bimodal for the entire dataset. However, this bimodality vanished for the older users. This lent credence to the claim that the bimodality is due to users rushing to and from work.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

A few were observed...

  • Exactly zero Customers used the Bike-Share-for-All plan.
  • Tuesday and Thursday seemed to consistently boast the highest trip-taking rates, regardless of age group.

There isn't a clear trend connecting all age groups but perhaps we don't have to connect all age groups. If we ignore the Midnight-to-Dusk trips, we can see that as the users get older the mean trip duration lengthens in the Late Morning period. One possible explanation for this is that the older users were not commuting to work, but instead perhaps taking recreational strolls, leisurely rides.

The trend breaks for the oldest users.

Multivariate plot 4: Start station, End station and Average trip duration¶

Let's ask - which journeys took the longest average time? A journey is simply a start station and end station pair.

Because there are so many start and end stations, we can't explore all possible journeys (there'd be at most $359*359$ possibilities!). Instead we'll only explore this for the top five most frequented start and end-stations. Even though that's a small sample of stations, it already gives a grid of 25 cells!

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The most important fact we observed is that the average trip duration for the afternoon period increased throughout the week, peaking on weekends. We also noticed that the older users, on average, generally had longer Late Morning/Early Afternoon trips compared to the younger ones.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

There weren't any interesting or surprising interactions.

Conclusions¶

Correlations with trip duration showed up more clearly in bivariate explorations.

  • We saw that most of the users were male.
  • We saw that the longest trip durations were associated with both the youngest and oldest users.
  • We saw that the trip duration (counts or average) correlated with user age, user type, start hour, weekday, and even start station, though the trends weren't always extreme.
  • We saw that the number of trips taken spiked in the Early Morning and Late Afternoon periods, and found evidence suggesting that it was due to users rushing to and from work.
  • We saw that the number of trips taken spiked on Tuesdays and Thursdays but there didn't seem to be enough data to draw anything meaningful from that.
  • We also remarked on how interesting it was that the counts for the start hour and end hour looked very similar and peaked at the same times. We suggested that this indicated the good logistics of the Bike-sharing programme, and the shorter trip durations overall.
